    "niche": "Synapse Data Warehousing, SQL Analytics Endpoints, and Distributed Compute",
    "question": "Explain how the Polaris engine translates an incoming T-SQL query into localized file-skipping parameters when evaluating complex WHERE clauses with nested OR conditions.",
    "answer": "Polaris parses WHERE clauses with nested OR conditions by: 1) Converting the expression to Disjunctive Normal Form (DNF). 2) For each OR branch, extracting the constant literals and matching them against the min/max statistics in the Parquet file metadata. 3) If any file's min/max range overlaps with the criteria in the OR branch, that file is included in the scan list. 4) If nested OR conditions are complex (e.g., `(A=1 AND B=2) OR (C=3)`), Polaris evaluates min/max bounds for each clause. If the columns are not sorted together, this can result in scanning all files, degrading performance. Sort columns used in complex filters to improve pruning efficiency.",
    "difficulty": "HARD"
