    "answer": "VARCHAR(MAX) columns are treated differently by the SQL Engine query memory manager. 1) The optimizer allocates a fixed, large memory size (often 8KB per row) for VARCHAR(MAX) columns, regardless of the actual string size. 2) In high-concurrency environments, running parallel hash aggregations on these columns rapidly consumes the query memory grant. 3) This leads to memory spills to disk, degrading query performance, or query failures with memory exhaustion errors. To fix, avoid VARCHAR(MAX) for aggregation or grouping columns; define appropriate maximum lengths (e.g., VARCHAR(256)) to allow the engine to allocate memory accurately.",
