    "answer": "1. Private Peering (Recommended): Traffic from the SHIR to Azure databases (like Azure SQL or Blob Storage) travels over a private connection without crossing the public internet. This provides maximum security and predictable latency.\n\n2. Microsoft Peering: Traffic routes to the public endpoints of Azure services. While still traversing the ExpressRoute circuit, it requires configuring NAT and firewall rules on your network perimeter to allow public IP routing.\n\n3. Performance: Private Peering provides lower latency and higher security because it avoids intermediate firewall checks. Microsoft Peering is necessary if you are accessing public APIs or services that do not support private endpoints, but it increases security auditing complexity.",
