    "answer": "1. Transaction Log Bloat: During large imports, if `writeBatchSize` is too high (e.g., 1 million rows), SQL Server holds a massive open transaction in memory, which can exhaust the transaction log space (`tempdb` and `ldf` files) and cause execution failures.\n\n2. Tuning values: Set `writeBatchSize` to a smaller value (e.g., 10,000 to 50,000 rows depending on row width). This forces ADF to commit transactions in smaller blocks, freeing transaction log space frequently.\n\n3. Timeout Tuning: Set `writeBatchTimeout` (e.g., `00:02:00` - 2 minutes) to ensure that if the SQL Server index lock takes too long to resolve, the batch times out and retries instead of holding transaction locks open indefinitely, protecting DB stability.",
