    "category": "ADF",
    "niche": "Triggers and Scheduling",
    "question": "How does trigger concurrency and queuing behavior work in Azure Data Factory when a pipeline run takes longer than the trigger interval?",
    "answer": "If a pipeline is triggered (e.g., every 5 minutes) but the previous run is still executing, the trigger's behavior depends on its configuration. By default, pipelines have no concurrency limits and will run in parallel. However, if you configure a pipeline-level concurrency limit (e.g., 1), ADF will queue the new run. The trigger registers the run, but it stays in a 'Queued' state. If the queue length exceeds the system limit (typically 100), ADF drops subsequent runs, causing trigger failures.",
