    "answer": "1. Sector Sizes: Modern drives use 4KB sector sizes. To support legacy OS, some use 512-byte emulation (512e).\n\n2. Alignment Penalty: If database files are misaligned with physical 4K sectors, a single 8KB page write will span across sector boundaries (e.g., crossing 3 sectors instead of 2). This forces the disk controller to execute a read-modify-write cycle, reading the entire sector, updating bytes, and writing it back. This doubles write latency and degrades transaction throughput under heavy write loads.",
