    "answer": "1. Join Reordering: The optimizer must decide the sequence of joins (e.g., `(A join B) join C`).\n\n2. Tree Types:\n- Left-Deep: Leaves represent tables, right inputs are intermediate results. Simple to evaluate but limits parallel execution.\n- Right-Deep: Left inputs are intermediate results. Useful for hash joins.\n- Bushy: Joins intermediate tables (e.g., `(A join B) join (C join D)`). Highly complex search space.\n\nTo manage compile time, the optimizer restricts its search to left-deep trees in Phase 0/1, and only evaluates bushy trees in Phase 2 under strict cost constraints.",
