    "answer": "1. The issue: MSTVFs act as black boxes. Historically, the optimizer assumed a static cardinality of 1 (or 100) rows, leading to bad join plans.\n\n2. Interleaved Execution: During query compilation, when the engine encounters an MSTVF, it pauses optimization. It runs the MSTVF physically, records the actual row count, and resumes optimization, using the real cardinality to build an accurate plan.",
