    "question": "Explain Intent Locks (IS, IX, SIX). Why are they critical for preventing concurrency race conditions between DML transactions and schema modifications (Sch-M)?",
    "answer": "1. Intent Locks: Indicated at higher levels (table, page) to flag that child resources (pages, rows) hold locks.\n\n2. Race Prevention: If transaction A holds an Exclusive lock on a row, it places an Intent Exclusive (IX) lock on the parent table. If transaction B requests a Schema Modification (Sch-M) lock to alter the table structure, the Sch-M request conflicts with the IX lock at the table level. Transaction B waits, preventing structural changes while rows are being updated.",
